		"boxes" : [ 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-19",
					"linecount" : 7,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 37.0, 378.0, 177.0, 100.0 ],
					"text" : "The faders allow you get a feel how a sigmoid or logit mapping would work on an input parameter. The plots show you the resulting curve depending on the parameter(s) steepness (and shift)."
				}

			}
, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-17",
					"linecount" : 5,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 21.0, 63.0, 669.0, 74.0 ],
					"text" : "This patch demonstrates the [sigmoid-logit] and [sigmoid-logit-shift] abstractions. Sigmoid/logit mappings map a linear input to an S-shaped curve giving preference to either the extremes (sigmoid) or center (logit), depending on the steepness. The abstractions are programmed to form a sigmoid curve when the steepness parameter is >0 and a logit curve when it is <0.\nIn the [sigmoid-logit-shift] case, there is another parameter called shift. This can be used to shift the S curve either along the x-axis (in the sigmoid case) or y-axis (in the logit case). This adds more continuous flexibility to the mapping."
				}

			}
, 			{
